ving rooms, and basements-in which their cognitive dependence on other characters inhabiting these spaces becomes clear. Figlerowicz highlights the diversity of aesthetic and sociopolitical contexts in which these affective dependencies become central to these authors' representations of selfhood. By setting these novels and poems in conversation with the work of contemporary theorists, she illuminates pressing and unanswered questions about subjectivity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Nov 2019) 0aAffect (Psychology) in literature. 0aDomestic space in literature. 0aLiterature, Moderny20th centuryxHistory and criticism. 0aModernism (Literature) 0aModernism (Literature). 0aSubjectivity in literature. 4aPhilosophy & Religion. 4aPhilosophy. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Semiotics & Theory.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCOR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017z978311066587108iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017z978311060673740uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9781501714245zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9781501714245.jpg  a978-3-11-060673-7  Cornell Univ. Press eBook-Package Pilot Project 2016-2017c2016d2017  a978-3-11-066587-1  COR eBook-Package Pilot Project 2017b2017  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_LS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_LS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA14ALL  aPDA16SSH  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA1ALL  aPDA2  aPDA2HUM  aPDA5EBK  aPDA7ENG